Austria
Introduction of a “budgetary gold rule” in the Constitution
The Government of great Social-Democratic coalition/Christian Democrat who is in the power in Austria has decided Tuesday to include in the Constitution a “budgetary gold rule” to reduce the public deficit and, thus, to avoid a possible degradation of the sovereign note of Austria on the part of the agencies of credit qualification (triple A).
He was the own Social-Democratic Chancellor, Werner Faymann, who announced this decision after a Cabinet, when the Austrian national debt reaches 74.6%, a number far beyond the maximum limit of 60% fixed by the Maastricht Agreement, but clearly inferior to the debts of countries like Italy, Greece or Spain.
“If the solution of Austria in a single level were reduced, of AAA to AA+, we would have to pay to 3,000 million Euros more in interests every year”, it indicated to the Vice chancellor Christian Democrat of Foreign Affairs, Michael Spindelegger.
Austria responds thus to a request of the Summit from Brussels to the Member States of the zone of the Euro of the past 26 of October: in her, the Government and Chiefs of State requested the inclusion, before end of 2012, of the reduction of the public deficit and the recovery of the balance of the public accounts in the Constitution or a Law with equivalent value.
The device adopted by the Austrian Government comes near to the “German model”, since Germany was the first European country that type of “rule” adopted.
Before 2017, the structural public deficit would have to diminish every year in a 0.75% of gross domestic product (PIB) and, as of the 2017, the structural public deficit of the federal State would not have to surpass every year 0.35% of the GDP, whereas the regional States, as well as the communes, would have to present budgets balances.
The objective consists of which, towards 2020/2021, the national debt is reduced under the criterion of 60% fixed by the Maastricht Agreement.
